The GAO report highlights a clear failure of congressional responsibility. With nearly half a trillion dollars in unauthorized spending, Congress must restore regular order and ensure taxpayer dollars are allocated with proper oversight.

The report also shows that Congress created entirely new accounts in the 2023 omnibus—programs never authorized by law—and provided them with over $1.5 BILLION in taxpayer dollars, bypassing standard oversight processes.
Even more concerning, $307 BILLION of that funding supports programs whose authorizations expired over a decade ago, some since 1980.

The findings are alarming: nearly $500 BILLION of FY2025 discretionary spending—29% of the total budget—is directed to programs operating without proper authorization or congressional review. https://t.co/8R47IIxD6G

Here is an example of how the provider tax scams work:

In a state, hospitals could agree to pay $10 million in provider taxes, and the state would increase Medicaid payments to hospitals by $20 million 

(not necessarily improving any benefits for the recipients - recently in IN $2.6B of Medicaid dollars were diverted by hospitals from the seniors in nursing homes).

Assuming the state had a 75% FMAP, the state would then receive $15 million in federal Medicaid matching funds (75% of $20 million).

As a result:

- hospitals would gain $10 million ($20 million in increased Medicaid payments minus $10 million in tax payments), 

- the state would gain $5 million ($25 million from the hospitals and the federal government minus the $20 million paid to the hospitals), 

and the federal government would pay  $15 million.
